---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Masthead from '../components/Masthead.astro';
import SiteFooter from '../components/SiteFooter.astro';
---
<Base
  title="Methodology — The Architecture of Tipsheet"
  description="How we fuse computational scale with elite editorial judgment. Discover the scoring rubric and grounding rules that power Tipsheet."
>
  <Masthead activeNav="methodology" />
  <main>
    <article class="editorial-page">
      <div class="kicker"><span>Methodology</span></div>
      <h1>The Architecture of Intelligence.</h1>
      <p class="dek" style="font-family: var(--serif); font-style: italic; font-weight: 300; font-size: 21px; line-height: 1.45; color: var(--text-soft); max-width: 36ch; text-wrap: balance;">
        How we fuse computational scale with elite editorial judgment to extract truth from regulatory noise.
      </p>

      <h2>The Materiality Index</h2>
      <p>Every disclosure fed into our pipeline is computationally scored on a 5–10 scale. This score measures <em>materiality</em>—how severely a filing alters the investment thesis—not the dramatic flair of the corporate language.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>9–10 (Catalytic)</strong> — Structural shifts. Governance breaks, massive capital raises, unguided M&amp;A, or severe regulatory actions.</li>
        <li><strong>7–8 (Consequential)</strong> — Meaningful deviations. Unanticipated order wins, credit rating upgrades/downgrades, and shifting margin guidance.</li>
        <li><strong>5–6 (Routine)</strong> — Expected cadence. Scheduled earnings releases and routine board approvals.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Filings scoring below 5 are categorized as noise. They are purged by our upstream classifiers and never see the light of publication.</p>

      <h2>The Computational Editorial Workflow</h2>
      <p>Tipsheet represents a paradigm shift in financial media: the synthesis of large language models (LLMs) with ruthless editorial constraints.</p>
      <p>Every article originates from a primary source—a BSE/NSE filing or an earnings transcript. Our extraction engine reads the raw document, isolating the mathematical realities and corporate admissions. This raw rationale is then passed to our LLM synthesis layer, which writes the final prose.</p>
      <p><strong>Crucially, the AI operates in a closed loop.</strong> It is mathematically forbidden from introducing external facts, scraping secondary news, or inventing sentiment. It cannot predict prices. It cannot invent quotes. Every output must survive an automated verification pass against the source document before it is committed to our database.</p>

      <h2>The Anatomy of a Note</h2>
      <p>We respect the reader's time. Therefore, every filing note adheres to a strict, scannable architecture:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>The Headline</strong> — Uncompromising, sentence-case declarations. The company is the subject; the verb is active.</li>
        <li><strong>The Number</strong> — The single most devastating or impressive metric from the filing, isolated for clarity.</li>
        <li><strong>What Happened</strong> — Three bullet points stripping the event down to its bare, undeniable facts.</li>
        <li><strong>Why This Matters</strong> — The editorial verdict. Contextualized consequence in two to three sentences.</li>
        <li><strong>The Full Read</strong> — A tightly wound narrative (120–200 words) that weaves the math and the implication into a singular thesis.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Absolute Grounding</h2>
      <p>Every metric, date, and percentage published on Tipsheet is tethered to the exchange filing. We do not engage in narrative spin. We do not write that "investors are worried" unless management explicitly addresses investor anxiety in the document. We describe the blast radius of an event; we do not presume to speak for the market.</p>
      <p>Outputs that fail our cryptographic or semantic grounding tests are incinerated by the pipeline.</p>

      <h2>The Banned Lexicon</h2>
      <p>Corporate communications and traditional financial media rely on a shared vocabulary of empty filler. We have hard-coded our models to reject it. You will never read the following phrases on Tipsheet:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><em>"Going forward", "In today's dynamic environment", "Notably"</em> (Padding)</li>
        <li><em>"Leverage", "Synergies", "Transformative", "Robust"</em> (Corporate clichés)</li>
        <li><em>"Paves the way", "Marks a milestone", "Underscores management's commitment"</em> (Manufactured narratives)</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Verification & Provenance</h2>
      <p>Trust requires auditability. Every single note published on Tipsheet includes a direct, outbound link to the raw BSE or NSE filing. We do not ask you to trust our computational pipeline; we invite you to verify our reading against the immutable primary source.</p>

      <p style="margin-top: 56px; padding-top: 32px; border-top: 1px solid var(--hairline); font-family: var(--mono); text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.1em; color: var(--text-muted); font-size: 10px;">
        V 2.0 // This methodology is computationally enforced.
      </p>
    </article>
  </main>
  <SiteFooter />
</Base>
